reviews.review_text: Turn it up to 11 Wow this show completely rocks and is perfect if your lookin for something that won't let you stand still.  The Matrix mix is excellent and is probably one of the best examples of the potential of this format, well done. What a show. Wish I was there. Get it, nuff said.
Great Stuff Just a smokin show with everyone soundeding tight as ever! Great show!! Must listen!

Really good... ...especially once the band gets cooking somehwere in the middle of the first set.  The second set, particularly out of space, really rocks.  The sound however is not "A No. 1."  Early the vocals are washed out, but the recording does seem to improve.  Of course, I am being nit picky here (but I was just listening to the Aud of one of the October Frost shows from this year, which is perfect)...this is a very good source.  And a border line great show.

The Scarlet-Fire The show overall is very solid.  It is the Scarlet-Fire, though, that blows me away.  I am a fan of this combination so have heard many.  This version is incredible, maybe the best I have ever listened to.  Highly recommend.

First tape I had The second set of this was the first dead boot tape I ever had, also the first sb tape I had, and is what really brought me to love live dead. 

Listening again today, I see why this is still one of the best shows I've ever heard. The scarlet=>fire is somking hot, est/eyes is great, uncle/truckin is great, and the morning dew is sublimely beautiful. 

Thank you, archivists.

Finally, Crystal-Clear, Out-Front Bobby In The Mix Little more needs to be said about this remarkable show in terms of musical performance
 The sound has an extremely "precise"
quality that is all too often missing in the best
soundboards. Every instrument is cleanly separated
and isolated. Weir is easy to follow and this
recording provides a great opportunity to study his art.
 Interestingly, the relative proportions of the
various channels  (very democratic, extremely atypical of Healy and Cutler) and the almost "hygienic" aural imagery are quite evocative of Owsley's mixing and editing style.

Lordy, lordy, look who is 40....... Ball buster of a show.  That second set seriously  stomps on the proverbial terra.   The mountain right across the valley from myself is on actually on fire, too.  Nice bonus.....

Neyessss My first review-Wheeee!
I was in the mood for an 80's "It's All Over Now". I warmed up with "Ramble on Rose", soundin' good. Then just what the doctor ordered. A smokin' version of "It's All Over Now". That song sounds fun to play.
Now I'm smiling, no need to look around the rest of the night.
The thing is this show has a mix that is very easy on the ears. It's like all the players have their volume set 'just exactly perfect', the instruments tones just sort of bloom.
This show would be great played on a reel-to-reel or vinyl through a tube amp. Wheeee!!

Drums. yes, drums Very good energy and superior clarity in recording.  Played loud enough on a good sound system one easily separates all the different toys a percussionist gets to play with.  I like these earlier forays into the drums/space theme before it became overextended excuse to chase the dragon midway through the set.  

A bounding Eyes seems to leave the Fat Man breathless as he can barely spit lyrics out before tearing into another solo.  No brakes on this machine. 

Overall a really fluid show without a bunch of delays in tuning and dinking around.  Well worth the listen, especially the Matrix format.

show of the tour yup cans o' beer in the infield - lone star!
kicked ass on the rocks and elsewhere. well the frost was primo too - once on the road though this was it!

Outstanding This show was the kind we followed them everywhere for. Hoping you get that show!!! we got it this night. Only down fall is encore. 
 I remember clearly getting back home after being on this summer tour waiting for east coast tour to start and getting these shows in the mail from a guy I met at Red Rocks, He sent me this night and next along with one of the Red Rocks shows. I can remember being very young and in total love with these guys. Had a bag of what back then was considered Killer Bud. Sat in my room for few days recovering from tour listening to these shows smoking and loving life. Another saying we use to use back then loving life.

Lovin it All the Sick Bits seem to be really good THANKS!  Nice Bird song, the vocals are really on thats nice to hear, and the jamming superb. There is 3 hours of music hear, what a show. You dont see shows this long much anymore. YAAR!

there were days and there were days between this is one of the days, not a day between show
a birthday show outdoors, like 74 
I watch/listen to this alot because it makes me smile and very happy to watch and hear Jerry and everybody having so much fun, 
and every time he looked to his left I know he was looking at me, smiling at him

Hot show + superb matrix Great '82 show from a really great run that started on July 25 in Tempe through August 10 in Iowa City.  This show in Austin was top notch, and this matrix captures it wonderfully - superb clarity with all the combined benefits of a good SBD and a crisp AUD.

The first set has some great versions of songs typically played in this era: starts off with a ripping Alabama>Promised Land, there's a playful and grooving Candyman, Bird Song is full of great exploratory playing by Jerry, we get a standout version of It's All Over Now where the band really stretches out, and a smoking hot Deal closes the set (my favorite 1st set closer of the early 80s).

The second set however is where things really take off. The Scarlet>Fire is one of the best of the early 80s, the entire band is firing on all cylinders, superb transition jam between the songs, they just nail it. That is followed by an emphatic Estimated where both Bobby and Jerry are tearing it up, which leads into a fast paced Eyes that breaks down into a Brent and Bobby fueled jam heading into D/S. From there we get great playing in a UJB>Truckin' transition before a stunning version of Morning Dew. The performance of Dew is a real highlight, Jerry's vocals and playing are top notch.

After a quick rip through Saturday Night the encore is a stunning It's All Over Now Baby Blue -- Jerry really nailed some Baby Blue encores in 82 (see also the Iowa City show) and this one is a truly great version.

This is a show that could easily be overlooked due to other landmark shows that occurred on the same date in previous years (Yale Bowl in 71, the 3-set 4 hour Wall of Sound show in Hartford in 74).  This 82 show, however, should not be missed if you enjoy this era of the band!
